In storage since.A scan from the owners manual, displayed here, shows how Mackie defines it as a 12 channel mixer.Includes padded Gig Skinz carry bag and Mackie dust cover.Includes optional 96kHz FireWire card that was originally available for streaming 14 independent channels of audio to computer.  Since Mackie stopped supporting drivers, it may or may NOT have that functionality on a Mac.  Definitely not on a Windows platform as of the last time I contacted Mackie in 2016.From Mackie: The Mackie Onyx 1220 12-Channel Mixer is a small-format analog mixer. Includes 4 boutique-class Onyx mic preamps with 3-band Perkins EQ plus sweepable mids on mic/line channels. . . .Includes aux sends with pre/post switches, 4 stereo line-level inputs, a talkback section for use with internal or external mics, true hardware EQ bypass, and a Planet-Earth switching power supply for worldwide use. Other features include individual 48V phantom power switches on all mic inputs; 60mm logarithmic taper faders for smooth, linear fades; and balanced direct outs for every channel via DB-25 connections. Selectable instrument inputs on the first 2 channels means no DI boxes are needed.Features    4 mic inputs    4 stereo line-level inputs    2 aux sends    Built-in Talkback section for use with internal or external mic    True hardware EQ bypass    Planet-Earth switching power supply for worldwide use    Individual 48V phantom power switches on all mic inputs    60mm Logarithmic Taper faders for smooth, linear fades    Balanced direct outs for every channel via DB-25 connections    Selectable Instrument inputs on first 2 channels - no DI box needed    17.3in/439mm H x 13.9in/353mm W x 5.9in/150mm DManual and schematics are posted on the Mackie site.  https://loudaudio.netx.net/portals/loud-public/#search/exact/onyx%201220 .Email correspondence through Craigslist Relay ONLY. -- REPEAT Craigslist Relay ONLY! Thank you kindly.

loud.name: Vintage Regal parlor guitar - needs neck reset
loud.description: Here is a “student” guitar made by in the 1940s by Regal Guitars (1896-1954) under the Federated Teachers Service Corp. label. It features an all-birch construction in brown sunburst. It plays as a Hawaiian right now ... but a neck reset can revert it back to Spanish.This one shows it age: the top shows some bloat, action is super high (see below), and there is some scuffing.Ah, but the tone—loud (the birch), deep, authoritative.Action: 1/8” at first fret, 3/8” at fifth. 1/2” at twelfth.Sorry, no case. Local pickup & CASH ONLY.

famous.name: Famous FS-1 Soprano Ukulele OBO
famous.description: Pretty little soprano, nice build with super-thin mahogany laminate, but with a sound that will rival most sold-wood ukes. Extremely light, with excellent projection and beautiful resonance. The FS-1 is a Japanese build, identical to the Kiwaya KS-1, but sold only to the Japanese market. This older uke has a Rosewood fingerboard, which you won't find in production any longer...the newer ones are walnut.  Nice, low action and great intonation. Friction tuners. Tiny scratch on the headstock, mark on the first fret - see the photos for detail. One-of-a-kind cloth gig bag included. Reasonable offers are welcome.

famous.name: Martin MSP7100 Lifespan SP Phosphor Bronze 3-pack 012/054 -- unopened
famous.description: This is an unopened 3-pack of the discontinued Martin Lifespan SP Phosphor Bronze MSP7100 Light Gauge Acoustic Guitar strings, .012/.016/.025/.032/.042/.054.I've stopped using coated strings altogether, so I'll never need these. They are just a couple of years old, sealed, and thus as good as new.These are no longer made so are hard to find. Martin was using Cleartone for the coating at this point, but since then they have formulated their own in-house coating which they now call Lifespan 2.0. I have not tried those strings so do not know how they compare. Perhaps because no licensing fees are involved, they are a bit cheaper.These sold for $19 each and sets of 3 would typically go for over $40. I scoured a site named after a famous Brasilian river to get an idea of what a fair price would be. The posted price is for three sets as it is an unopened box.

famous.name: 1920s Oscar Schmidt stencil guitar - great shape , great tone
famous.description: 1930s Oscar Schmidt stencil guitar featuring a Hawaiian scene.Solid birch—the shape and silhouette is quite like their famous Stella. It has that deep, satisfying sound too.There are some repaired cracks along the upper bout, scuffs and stencil discoloring, but generally the guitar is in great shape. Stamped on the top of the headstock is “FATDOG 93.”Going with the theme, I have set this up, with a vintage nut riser, to be played lap style like a Hawaiian guitar.Without the nut extender the relatively high action measures 1/16” at first fret, 2/16” at seventh fret and 3/16” at twelfth fret (see last photos).In all, an enjoyable guitar - both visually and sonically - that is a playable work of art.NEW gig bag included (not shown).Local pick up only; CASH ONLY.
